</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="31" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="31">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="31">
The unique type seen appears to be a member of the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="31">puncticollis</emphasis>
group. I have been unable to examine the genitalia, but the general structure is similar to the species of this group (I observed 4 setiferous punctures in interval 3 contrary to 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Putzeys’">Putzeys'</normalizedToken>
original description which mentions 3 punctures). The species appears to be most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Valdés" authorityYear="2012" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Semiardistomis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exspectatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="31">Semiardistomis exspectatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. n.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
